  "text": " Hi, I'm Kathy and welcome to Youmonic. This short upcoming video that you're about to watch will discuss the course objectives for a corporate memory improvement course and reasons how this course can give you a substantial competitive advantage over your peers in your own organization. Let me now pass you over to my colleague, Pete. Enjoy. We live in a highly competitive corporate environment. Most organizations almost always have a couple of employees aspiring for that one opening promotion, making the corporate environment even more competitive among peers. As corporate employees, we are expected to have a wide variety of skills in a setting, such as teamwork, decision-making, leadership, true management, verbal, and written communication. Another skill that is just as important is the skill of memory. Having a good memory isn't just about remembering where you parked your car or left your keys. In fact, it goes deeper than that. Let me give you an example. Let's say there are two potential candidates, Steve and Susan, competing for an upcoming promotion within a company. Steve has trouble remembering the names of the people he meets. Steve also forgets upcoming appointments or tasks that he needs to do such as sending an email out to a fellow colleague by the end of the workday When Steve is presenting in a meeting he unable to recall facts and figures instantly when his peers or superiors request information from him As a result, Steve has to look through his notes or tell them that he has to get back to them. When Steve goes in to pitch to a new potential client, he's unable to effectively memorize, retain, and then recall information about that client. Yes, he may have done his research before going in for that pitch, but due to his bad memory, he finds that he needs a lot of time to memorize such crucial details. Steve is flogged with work on a daily basis. I mean, can we really blame Steve? For such is the current corporate environment. So, is this normal that he forgets these things? Although these lapses in memory may seem normal, it's not. These lapses in Steve's memory make him seem incompetent. Susan, on the other hand, has mastered the skill of working in a corporate environment. She has all the skills mentioned earlier, such as teamwork, decision-making, leadership, time management, and communication skills. She recently acquired the skill of memory techniques to add on to her skills tool belt. When Susan meets people, she's able to perfectly remember and then recall their name years later. Susan knows her figures She able to perfectly recall the entire financial history of the company financial data by memory thus impressing her superiors It only took her 10 minutes to memorize all those numbers because of her effective memory techniques that she uses When Susan gives a presentation to her peers or board members, she's able to recall all necessary information without having to look through her notes. When pitching to a new potential client, it took her 10 minutes to memorize all the important facts about that client, such as their latest financial figures, all the names of the board members, the organization's timeline, their current client list, as well as all other important information about that client. This makes her seem highly competent. Is she smarter than Steve? Not really. All she has are the right memory techniques to help her out with her daily professional tasks. There's an irony here. One does not have to be smart to have a good memory, but having a good memory makes others perceive you as being highly intelligent. With regards to the story about Steve and Susan, there are hundreds of other situations where someone with a good knowledge of memory improvement techniques can gain a substantial advantage over someone who doesn't. The memory skills that you'll learn in this course are easy to understand and apply to your job regardless of which department within the organization you work in Whether it be HR finance engineering operations marketing IT legal or training and development it does not even matter which level you belong to within your organizational structure whether you're senior management or an intern for the company. This online memory improvement course is designed and developed for anyone working in a corporate environment, and that is you. In this online course, you will learn how to, one, effectively memorize names of people in a professional context. One topic within that section covers how to remember names of multiple people when you meet them all at once. Two, you'll also learn how to look professional and confident when giving a speech or presentation without the use of notes and much, much more. This online memory improvement course is also taught by a professional instructor, Mr. Sancy, who's held the world memory record for the longest color sequence memorized and has also competed in the world memory championships which is the olympic equivalent of memorization sport the memory improvement skills that you'll learn in this online course will last a lifetime this is one of the best corporate skills that you can add on to your already growing professional skill set for more information or to learn more about our online memory improvement course visit us at umonic.com. Gain a competitive advantage over your peers today.",
